<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12031g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12031g">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12031g"> 31(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Pisciferos amnes, multo salmone feraces</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Je me contenterai de vous dire en langue vulgaire qu&apos;on p&eacute;chait dans la baie des saumons, des lamproies, des congres, des marsouins, des soles, des turbots, etc; le saumon &eacute;tait abondant; un po&egrave;te du XIIIe si&egrave;cle a dit en parlant des rivi&egrave;res qui se jettent dans l&apos;estuaire normand-breton: <i>Pisciferos amnes, multo salmone feraces</i>. On a m&ecirc;me pr&eacute;tendu que les saumons &eacute;taient si communs que les domestiques des fermes du <font color="green">[142]</font> rivage stipulaient, dans leur contrat de louage de services qu&apos;on ne pourrait les nourrir de saumon plus de deux fois la semaine. C&apos;est une l&eacute;gende; on la retrouve m&ecirc;me en Angleterre. <br><font color="green">[I will restrict myself to telling you in the vernacular that one used to fish in the bay for salmon, lamprey and conger eel, porpoise, sole, turbot, etc; the salmon was abundant; a poet of the thirteenth century said of the rivers that feed the Normand-Breton estuary: <i><mark>Pisciferos amnes, multo salmone feraces</mark></i>. One has even said that the salmon were so common that the farm servants of the river shores stipulated in their contracts that they could only eat salmon twice a week. This is a legend that one can also hear in England.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 142-3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Latin <i>Pisciferos amnes, multo salmone feraces</i>: fishful streams, rich in salmon. </mm> </dd></dl>
